Cleanup Phase 2 (helper #1): consolidate 18 HTML escapers into campistry_utils.js

The single most-duplicated logic in the codebase: 22 files each defined their own HTML
escaper (named esc / escHtml / escapeHtml / _escHtml), grown over 10 months into
DIVERGENT variants (some escaped & < > " ', some only & < >, some the textContent trick).

Added campistry_utils.js -> window.CampUtils.escapeHtml, the canonical COMPLETE escaper
(& < > " '), loaded FIRST on flow/me/dashboard/go/index (anchored before
campistry_security.js). Wiring verified: every page that loads a converted file also
loads the util (0 gaps). Replaced 18 escaper copies with a 1-line delegation
(call sites unchanged -- the local function name + signature are preserved).

SECURITY BONUS: ~10 of those copies were the incomplete textContent-trick / &<>"-partial
escapers that did NOT escape quotes -- the same attribute-breakout XSS class fixed across
the v2 audit, in files the audit hadn't covered. Delegating UPGRADES them to the complete
escaper. Notably print_center.escHtml was textContent-only yet used inside data-* ATTRIBUTES
-> a latent quote-breakout gap now closed.

Deliberately NOT consolidated (the careful part):
- campistry_me.esc: its sibling je() does esc(s).replace(/'/g,"\\'") and DEPENDS on esc
  leaving ' raw. Escaping ' would break je's JS-string building. Left as-is.
- campistry_security.escapeHtml: escapes MORE (& < > " ' / backtick, OWASP-hardened);
  delegating would be a security DOWNGRADE. Left as-is.
- auto_validator/post_edit_system function esc(e): Escape-KEY handlers, not HTML escapers.

node --check: 19/19 OK. Live-verify after the preview rebuilds.

